    {
      "prompt": "Draw the recursion tree for T(n) = 2T(n/2) + n and use it to derive the time complexity. Why does this come out to O(n log n)?",
      "response": "0.\n\nA: Because n is the number of elements in the list.\nE.g., The list is [1,2,3,4,5,6] and n = 5. Then list length is 5 and we have n/5 elements.\nNow, we have n/5 elements in the list. So the arithmetic complexity is O(n/5 log n).\n\nA: Let's see. In one pass, we find the median for each element individually. Then, for the list, we take the median and compute the average of the elements. The average is O(n) because we have n elements to average. The median is O(n log n) because each element has an O(log n) chance of being the median.\nFor the average, how many elements have to be averaged? 1. Each element has at most 1/n. So the average is O(n/1).\nThe median is n/2. So the average is O(n/2).\nThe median is n/4. So the average is n/4.\nSo the average is O(n/2 log n).\n\nA: The average is O(n log n) because each element has an O(log n) chance to be the median.\nEach element has O(1) chance to be the median.\nSo the sum of the O(log n) elements is O(n log n).\nThe average of each element, O(n/log n).\nThe median is O(n/2) because each element has an O(log n) chance to be the median.\nThe average of the O(log n) elements is O(n/2)",
      "gold": "Recursion trees turn algebra into a picture. Let's build it carefully, level by level.\n\nAt the root, you have a single problem of size n, doing n work (the non-recursive part).\n\nWhat happens at the next level? The root spawns 2 children, each of size n/2. How much work does each child do? n/2 each. So the level total is 2 x (n/2) = n.\n\nLevel 3: each of those 2 nodes spawns 2 more, giving 4 nodes of size n/4. Work per node: n/4. Level total: 4 x (n/4) = n.\n\nDo you see the pattern? Every level sums to n. That's not a coincidence — it happens because the branching factor (2) exactly matches the inverse of the size reduction (1/2). The work fans out and shrinks at the same rate.\n\nNow, two more questions you must answer for any recursion tree: How many levels are there? And what's the work at the leaves?\n\nLevels: we keep halving until size 1. Starting at n, after k halvings the size is n/2^k. Setting that to 1: k = log_2(n). So there are log n + 1 levels.\n\nLeaves: there are 2^(log n) = n leaves, each doing O(1) work, totaling n.\n\nSumming all levels: (log n + 1) levels each contributing n = n(log n + 1) = O(n log n).\n\nThis is exactly merge sort's recurrence. The intuition: log n levels of dividing, and n work per level to merge. Whenever you see balanced halving plus linear combining, expect n log n."
